{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487210","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487210"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:01:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:01:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"278"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582541","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582541"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T06:46:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T06:46:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"278"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"278","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/278"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.14,0.14,0.48,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"278"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100359"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"278","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/278"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"278"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82762"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4341"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14306"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31749"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34499"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42995"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100359","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100359"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents as a new patient to the General Practice clinic with her partner to discuss preconception care. She has never been pregnant before. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her BMI is 22 kg/m2. They ask about recommended nutritional supplements during pregnancy and as such the doctor enquires into her medical history to help guide the recommendations.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following scenarios is most appropriate for recommending standard dose folate supplementation (as opposed to high-dose) in pregnancy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Woman has type 1 diabetes mellitus","Woman has inflammatory bowel disease","BMI 36 kg/m2","Woman is taking sertraline for depression","Family history of neural tube defects"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFolate supplementation is crucial for all women planning pregnancy or in early pregnancy to reduce the risk of neural tube defects. The standard dose of folate supplementation is 0.4-0.5 mg/day, while high-dose supplementation is 5 mg/day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWoman is taking sertraline for depression\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate scenario for recommending standard dose folate supplementation. Antidepressants, including selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs) like sertraline, are not associated with abnormal folate metabolism or increased risk of neural tube defects. Therefore, women taking antidepressants do not require high-dose folate supplementation and can be advised to take the standard dose.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWoman has type 1 diabetes mellitus\u003C/strong\u003E is an indication for high-dose folate supplementation. Diabetes, both type 1 and type 2, is associated with an increased risk of neural tube defects, and women with diabetes are recommended to take 5 mg/day of folate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWoman has inflammatory bowel disease\u003C/strong\u003E is also an indication for high-dose folate supplementation. Inflammatory bowel disease is a malabsorptive disorder, which can interfere with folate absorption. Women with malabsorptive disorders are recommended to take 5 mg/day of folate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBMI 36 kg/m2\u003C/strong\u003E is another scenario where high-dose folate supplementation is recommended. Women with a BMI \u0026gt; 30 kg/m2 are advised to take 5 mg/day of folate due to the increased risk of neural tube defects associated with obesity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFamily history of neural tube defects\u003C/strong\u003E is a clear indication for high-dose folate supplementation. Women with a personal or family history of neural tube defects are at higher risk and should take 5 mg/day of folate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther scenarios where high-dose folate supplementation is recommended include women taking anti-epileptics or folate antagonists (e.g. methotrexate, sulfonamides), women who smoke, and women belonging to high-risk ethnic groups (Celtic and Northern Chinese). For all other women without these specific risk factors, standard dose folate supplementation is appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["High-dose (5 mg/day) folate supplementation is recommended for pregnant women with certain risk factors, including diabetes, malabsorptive disorders, BMI \u003E 30 kg/m2, past/family history of neural tube defects, use of anti-epileptics or folate antagonists, smoking, or belonging to high-risk ethnic groups.","Standard dose (0.4-0.5 mg/day) folate supplementation is recommended for all other pregnant women without these specific risk factors."],"references":["The Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RANZCOG). Pre-pregnancy Counselling (C-Obs 3a). Melbourne: RANZCOG; 2017. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Pre-pregnancy-Counselling-C-Obs-3a.pdf","Dorney E, Black KI. Preconception care. Aust J Gen Pract. 2018;47(7):424\u2013429. Available from: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2018/july/preconception-care"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82762"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"278"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82762","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82762"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-25T14:54:59+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-25T14:55:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"278"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100359"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null}